# Java package structure

Base package: `com.dev.franrs.reservation`

Place new code in the subpackage that matches its role. Keep the application class at the root package.

| Package | Contents |
|---------|----------|
| `config` | Spring configuration: `WebMvcConfigurer`, CORS, `@Configuration` classes, explicit beans. |
| `controller` | REST controllers (`@RestController`); HTTP mapping only, delegate to services. |
| `dto` | API payloads: request/response records or classes (e.g. `CrearReservaRequest`), not JPA entities. |
| `entity` | JPA entities (`@Entity`), and enums persisted or tightly coupled to entities (e.g. status enums). |
| `exception` | Domain/runtime exceptions for business rules and global handlers (`@RestControllerAdvice`, `@ExceptionHandler`). |
| `repository` | Spring Data JPA repositories (`JpaRepository`, etc.). |
| `service` | Business logic (`@Service`), transactions, orchestration; no HTTP-specific types in method signatures when avoidable. |

**Root package (`com.dev.franrs.reservation`)**  
- Only the Spring Boot main class (`*Application`).

**Rules**

- Do not put entities or repositories inside `controller` or `service` source files; one top-level type per file, under the correct package.
- Cross-cutting API types used only in controllers may stay in `dto`; shared error bodies can live next to `exception` handlers if you add them later.
